description:
Final pass: This was missed because reviewers focused on individual function error handling, not the composition.

Root cause: In lichen_log_link_local_from_eui64 at lines 284-300:

  ret = lichen_eui64_to_iid(eui64, iid);
  if (ret < 0) {
      LOG_ERR(...);
      if (ll_addr_out != NULL) { memset(ll_addr_out, 0, ...); }
      return ret;  // <-- Returns error
  }

  ret = lichen_make_link_local(iid, &ll_addr);
  if (ret < 0) {
      LOG_ERR(...);
      if (ll_addr_out != NULL) { memset(ll_addr_out, 0, ...); }
      return ret;  // <-- Returns error
  }

This is actually correct - errors are propagated. The code defensively zeros ll_addr_out on error paths.

However, there's a subtle issue: iid is a stack variable (line 272: uint8_t iid[8];) that is NOT zeroed on error. After lichen_eui64_to_iid fails, iid contains undefined/uninitialized data. This doesn't matter because we return early, but if the code is later modified to continue after an error (e.g., best-effort mode), the uninitialized iid could leak.

Actually, lichen_eui64_to_iid only fails on NULL input, and we checked eui64 != NULL at line 276-282 before calling it. So the failure is unreachable... except for a modified iid parameter internally.

Looking at lichen_eui64_to_iid (lines 48-69 in ipv6_addr.c):
  if (eui64 == NULL || iid == NULL) { return -EINVAL; }
  memcpy(iid, eui64, 8);
  iid[0] ^= UL_BIT;
  return 0;

Since we pass a valid stack array for iid, the only failure mode is eui64==NULL (which we already checked). So the error path at 285-291 is defensive but unreachable from normal code paths.

Not a bug - the code is defensively correct.
